{{short description|Oceanid in Greek mythology}} {{Other uses|Acaste}} {{Infobox deity|type=Greek |name=Acaste or Akastê |deity_of=Companion of [[Persephone]] |member_of=the[[Oceanids]] |image= |alt= |caption= |other_names= |hiro= |affiliation= |cult_center= |abode= |animals= |symbol= |consort= |parents=[[Oceanus]] and [[Tethys (mythology)|Tethys]] |siblings=Other Oceanids and the [[Potamoi]] |offspring= |predecessor= |successor= |Roman_equivalent= |Etruscan_equivalent= }} In [[Greek mythology]], '''Acaste''' ({{IPAc-en|ə|ˈ|k|æ|s|t|iː}}; Ancient Greek: Ακαστη ''Akas''tê "unstable" or "irregular "'';'' feminine form of [[Acastus]]) was one of the [[Oceanids]], sea [[nymph]] daughters of the sea deities, [[Oceanus]] and [[Tethys (mythology)|Tethys]].<ref name=":0">[[Hesiod]]. ''[[Theogony]]'', ''[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.01.0130:card=337&highlight=acaste 346]'' {{PD-notice}}</ref>
== Family == Hesiod mentioned Acaste as one of the Oceanids:
: ''"Cerceis lovely of form, and soft eyed [[Plouto (Oceanid)|Pluto]], [[Perse (mythology)|Perseis]], [[Ianeira]], '''Acaste''', Xanthe, Petraea the fair, Menestho, and [[Europa (Greek myth)|Europa]], [[Metis (mythology)|Metis]], and [[Eurynome (Oceanid)|Eurynome]], and [[Telesto (mythology)|Telesto]] saffron-clad, [[Chryseis (mythology)|Chryseis]] and [[Asia (mythology)|Asia]] and charming [[Calypso (mythology)|Calypso]], Eudora, and [[Tyche]], Amphirho, and [[Ocyrhoe|Ocyrrhoe]], and [[Styx]] who is the chiefest of them all. These are the eldest daughters that sprang from Ocean and Tethys; but there are many besides."''
== Mythology == Acaste only appeared in one myth, along with her sisters, she was one of the companions of [[Persephone]] when the maiden she was abducted by [[Hades]], the god of the [[Underworld]]. Persephone recounted her kidnapping to her mother [[Demeter]] in the following passage:
: ''"All we were (i.e. Persephone and her companions) playing in a lovely meadow, [[Leucippe]] and Phaeno and [[Electra (Greek myth)|Electra]] and Ianthe, [[Melite (mythology)|Melita]] also and Iache with [[Rhodos|Rhodea]] and [[Callirhoe (mythology)|Callirhoe]] and Melobosis and [[Tyche]] and [[Ocyrhoe]], fair as a flower, Chryseis, Ianeira, '''Acaste''' and [[Admete]] and [[Rhodope (mythology)|Rhodope]] and Pluto and charming Calypso; Styx too was there and [[Urania]] and lovely Galaxaura with [[Athena|Pallas]] who rouses battles and [[Artemis]] delighting in arrows: we were playing and gathering sweet flowers in our hands, soft crocuses mingled with irises and hyacinths, and rose-blooms and lilies, marvellous to see, and the narcissus which the wide earth caused to grow yellow as a crocus."<ref name=":1">[[Homeric Hymns]]''.'' ''To Demeter, [http://94.70.254.130:8080/topostextnew/work.php?work_id=355#405 405]'' {{PD-notice}}</ref>''
