In [[Greek mythology]], the name '''Asterodia''', '''Asterodeia''', or '''Asterodea''' ({{IPAc-en|æ|s|t|ə|ˈ|r|ɒ|d|i|ə}}; [[Ancient Greek]]: Ἀστεροδεία, Ἀστεροδία) refers to:
*Asterodia, a daughter of [[Deioneus|Deion]] and [[Diomede]].<ref>Hard, pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA435 435], [https://books.google.com/books?id=r1Y3xZWVlnIC&pg=PA565 565]; [[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Apollodorus]], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Apollod.+1.9.4 1.9.4]; cf. [[Hesiod]], ''[[Catalogue of Women]]'' fr. 58.</ref> She is probably the same as the Asterodia (Asteria)<ref>Smith, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0104:entry=phocus-bio-2&highlight=asterodia "Phocus"].</ref> who bore [[Crisus]] and [[Panopeus (mythology)|Panopeus]] to [[Phocus]].<ref>[[Tzetzes]] on [[Lycophron]], 939</ref><ref>[[Scholia]] on ''[[Iliad]]'', 2.520</ref> *Asterodia, a [[Caucasus|Caucasian]] [[nymph]], daughter of [[Oceanus]] and [[Tethys (mythology)|Tethys]], mother of [[Absyrtus]] by [[Aeetes]].<ref>[[Apollonius of Rhodes]], ''[[Argonautica]]'', [https://archive.org/stream/argonautica00apoluoft#page/210/mode/2up 3.241&ndash;243]; for her parents see Conti, [https://books.google.com/books?id=WIglAQAAIAAJ&dq=Asterodia+Aeetes&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Asterodia p. 478] [https://books.google.com/books?id=WIglAQAAIAAJ&dq=Asterodia+Aeetes&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=A.R.+242 n. 23]; Preston's note to Apollonius of Rhodes, ''Argonautica'' 3.330 "''Asterodea''" ([https://archive.org/stream/bub_gb_TSVAAAAAYAAJ#page/n175/mode/1up p. 168]); [[scholia]] on [[Apollonius of Rhodes]], ''[[Argonautica]]'' 3.242 ([https://archive.org/stream/bub_gb_oBI-AAAAcAAJ#page/n267/mode/1up Parisian], [https://archive.org/stream/bub_gb_oBI-AAAAcAAJ#page/n576/mode/1up Florentine]).</ref> *Asterodia, one of the possible wives of [[Endymion (mythology)|Endymion]].<ref>Smith, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0104:entry=endymion-bio-1&highlight=asterodia Endymion]; [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Paus.+5.1.4 5.1.4]</ref> *Asterodia, daughter of [[Eurypylus#Other characters|Eurypylus]] and one of the possible wives of [[Icarius of Sparta|Icarius]].<ref>[[Pherecydes of Leros|Pherecydes]] in [[scholia]] on [[Homer]], ''[[Odyssey]]'', 15.16</ref>
