[[it:Formazioni nevose perenni#Nevaio]]

{{Infobox ecoregion |name=Sierra Juárez and San Pedro Mártir pine-oak forests |image=Paisaje con nieve.jpg |map=Sierra Juarez and San Pedro Martir Pine-Oak Forests map.svg |biome=[[Temperate coniferous forests]] |area=4000 |climate= [[Mediterranean climate|Mediterranean]] |country=[[Mexico]] |state=[[Baja California]] }} The '''Sierra Juárez and San Pedro Mártir pine-oak forests''' is an [[ecoregion]], in the [[Temperate coniferous forests]] [[biome]], that covers the higher elevations of the [[Sierra de Juárez|Sierra Juárez]] and [[Sierra San Pedro Mártir]] ranges, of the [[Peninsular Ranges]], in the northern [[Baja California Peninsula]] of [[Mexico]],<ref>National Geographic. 2001</ref> near the border with [[California]] ([[United States]]).
==Setting== The ecoregion covers an area of {{convert|4000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}. It lies at the southeastern extent of the [[Mediterranean climate]] region that covers much of California and the northwestern corner of [[Baja California]], and the climate is [[temperate]] with winter rains.
The pine-oak forests are bounded by the southern extent of the [[California chaparral and woodlands]] to the west, by the [[Baja California Desert]] to the southwest, and by the [[Sonoran Desert]] to the east.
==Flora== These forests are predominantly [[pine]], [[juniper]], [[fir]], and [[oak]]. Ten pine species can be found in the ranges, including [[Lodgepole Pine|Tamarack Pine (''Pinus contorta'' subsp. ''murrayana'')]], [[Pinus lambertiana|Sugar Pine (''Pinus lambertiana'')]], [[Parry Pinyon|Parry Pinyon ''(Pinus quadrifolia)'']], along with [[Abies concolor|White Fir (''Abies concolor'' subsp. ''lowiana'')]], and [[Calocedrus|California Incense Cedar (''Calocedrus decurrens'')]]. Oak species include [[Quercus agrifolia|Coast Live Oak (''Quercus agrifolia'')]], [[Quercus engelmannii|Engelmann Oak (''Quercus engelmannii'')]], [[Quercus chrysolepis|Canyon Live Oak (''Quercus chrysolepis'')]], [[Quercus peninsularis|Baja Oak (''Quercus peninsularis'')]]., and [[Quercus tomentella|Island Oak (''Quercus tomentella'')]]. There are also several isolated strands of aspens ([[Populus tremuloides]]) on the higher altitudes.
[[Cupressus forbesii|Tecate Cypress (''Cupressus forbesii'')]] and [[Cupressus arizonica|San Pedro Martir Cypress (''Cupressus arizonica'' subsp. ''Montana'')]] are found in scattered groves across the range. The Sierra Juárez and San Pedro Mártir pine-oak forests are near the southern limit of the distribution of the [[Washingtonia filifera|California Fan Palm (''Washingtonia filifera'')]].<ref>C. Michael Hogan. 2009</ref> The higher portions of these Peninsular Ranges harbor many rare and [[Endemism|endemic]] species.
