{{Unreferenced|date=February 2007}}

The '''sycamine tree''' ({{Lang-el|συκάμινος}} ''sykaminοs'')<ref>{{LSJ|suka/minos|συκάμινος|ref}}.</ref> is a tree mentioned{{Refn|group=n|In the [[dative case]] form of the word, i.e. {{lang|grc|συκαμίνῳ}} ''sykaminōi''.}} in [[Gospel of Luke|Luke]] 17:6 of the [[Bible]]. It is rendered by Luther as "[[mulberry]] tree", which is most probably the correct rendering. It is found in two species, the [[Black Mulberry|black mulberry]] (''Morus nigra'') and the [[White Mulberry|white mulberry]] (''Morus alba''), which are common in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]].  It is in the same [[family (biology)|family]] as the [[ficus|fig]]-tree. Some contend, however, that this name denotes the [[sycamore fig]] ({{lang|grc|συκομορέα}} ''sykomorea'')<ref>{{LSJ|sukomore/a|συκoμορέα|shortref}}.</ref> of Luke 19:4.

